gerber state bank argenta il  trust    trust department trust department product profiles agency accounts customer hires the gerber state bank to assume certain duties regarding their investments definition of agency account a relationship where a customer hires the gerber state bank through a letter of instruction agency agreement to assume certain duties regarding their investments the duties are disclosed in the agreement which can be terminated in writing the client then turns over their assets to the bank and we will manage them according to the instructions in the agency agreement custodial account this is a simple but complete administrative and custodial service we perform all the accounting record keeping and income collection duties for investments and safekeeping privileges investment management account includes all custodial duties plus investment management and advice we accept investment responsibility under guidelines established in the agency agreement important services safekeeping record keeping regular reports tax worksheets timely collection and investment of income skilled advice for investments bill paying and farm management trusts customer hires the gerber state bank to manage assets placed within the trust as trustee features benefits testamentary trust trust created through a will living trust trust created through present trust agreement revocable customer can terminate the trust at any time irrevocable customer gives up the right to terminate the trust why a trust investment management provide funds to you and others continues uninterrupted if incapacitated or after death avoids glare of publicity from probate timely and accurate record keeping prevents dissipation of assets spend thrift provisions can be implemented minors or special needs provisions can be invoked important services safekeeping record keeping regular reports tax worksheets timely collection and investment of income skilled advice for investments bill paying and farm management other fiduciary accounts products that can be utilized in the banks trust department features benefits corporate executorship trust department acts as executor and administrator through entire estate process why the trust department estate administration is complicated with dozens of duties as a financial manager required along with continuing communication with family members the bank is better prepared to handle emotional issues that may arise power of attorney trust department takes this fiduciary role as financial estate outlined by the power of attorney document and state statutes this may include collecting receipts paying of bills make investments manage andor sell property etc this can continue during the lifetime of the individual exercising the power of attorney charitable trust and foundations more comprehensive estate planning vehicle this product is mainly used by high net worth customers or individuals without family that have strong charitable attributes guardianshipconservatorship court appointed to protect financial estate of minor or disabled child or adult must report all receipts and disbursements to court on a timely basis retirement plans individual self directed iras business kprofit sharing plans simple k plans member fdic  equal housing lender  member cbai home  about us  locations  atm locations  online banking  deposit accounts  health savings accounts  deposit rates  gerber   loans  calculators  other products  trust department  community connections  privacy policy   secgems gerber family irrevocable trust  cncg  data feeds now available excel  csv  java  python etc database learn more gerber family irrevocable trust    otcqb    cncg  info ownership filings  commonwealth trust company trustee  bancroft mills rd wilmington  de   usa  filing datecurrent and former nameschanged on date gerber family irrevocable trust central index key cik  state of incorporation de country of incorporation usa fiscal year end  all related personscompanies filings concierge technologies inc   starfest inc  db  things to know before setting up an irrevocable trust  how to protect your assets how to protect your assets menu  things to know before setting up an irrevocable trust thinking about setting up an irrevocable trust when it comes to setting up a trust many don’t realize the key differences between a revocable and irrevocable trust before you sign on the dotted line there are a few things you should know about irrevocable trusts you give up your rights with irrevocable truststo distinguish the key differences between a revocable and irrevocable trust the name says it all once you set up a revocable trust it’s not set in stone trustees can make changes to the trust during their lifetime at their discretion if you change your mind about leaving your home and a million dollars to your ungrateful son you can remove his name as beneficiarywith an irrevocable trust once the grantor does the initial setup the trustee takes over that means you can’t go back and rewrite or remove the terms of the trust even if there is an exception the trustee and all parties involved would have to agree to the changes even the beneficiaries would need to agree that’s a hard pill to swallow about assets you once ownedirrevocable trusts are beneficial tools for estate planningyou might be wondering why you’d want to get involved in a trust that’s so final irrevocable trusts have some nice tax benefits for estate purposes you’re able to place some property within the trust to reduce the taxable value some assets are also sheltered from estate taxes at the time of the grantor’s death and distribution there are some other pros to no longer having ownership of assets in an irrevocable trust in the event of issues with creditors it protects your estate since the assets belong to the trustee after setup creditors can’t seize assets to reconcile outstanding debts even in the case of a bankruptcy the assets will stay put in the irrevocable trustirrevocable trusts require maintenanceit may not be as simple as you think to setup an irrevocable trust the process is more than just a onetime setup irrevocable trusts require upfront and continuous fees for maintenance and to pay staff the least expensive trust will cost a few thousand dollars to setup you’ll also have to pay a trust attorney to make sure the trust is organized correctly with the most benefitsdeciding whether to set up an irrevocable trust all boils down to what you need it to do for you in the end even revocable trusts transition to irrevocable after the death of the grantor no one can make changes to the terms the decision depends on if you want to have control and flexibility during your lifetime or the tax benefits to work for everyone now and later tweet recent posts  mistakes to avoid when setting up a living trust how a dapt domestic asset protection trust can protect your assets from creditors  things to know before setting up an irrevocable trust form an llc and protect your personal assets asset protection planning the basics to get you started the dos and don’ts of setting up a trust fund learn about revocable living trusts and why they should matter to youcategoriesasset protectionestate planningfamily trustirrevocable trustliving trustllcrevocable trusttrust fundtypes of wills gerber family irrevocable trust  ceo founder businessman  profile directorpedianet  list of ceos founders board members and company directors gerber family irrevocable trust check out list of companies and businesses related to gerber family irrevocable trust find out gerber family irrevocable trust address and contact details view other people related to gerber family irrevocable trust  coworkers colleagues companions etc address commonwealth trust company trustee  bancroft mills rd wilmington  de companies related to gerber family irrevocable trust cikcompany namepositioncompany addressconcierge technologies inc valley center rd k valley center  gerber f